3 seems to be most likely!

I think I'm going to have the worst score on this question out of all questions I've forecast so far! Absolute Brier bomb and painful lesson.

Novavax is likely out of the running for 2021: "the company’s issues are more concerning than previously understood, according to two of the people with direct knowledge of the matter." "it is generally understood that each vaccine batch should reach at least 90 percent. The company has struggled to attain anywhere close to that, one of the people with direct knowledge of the situation said. Another person familiar with the company’s manufacturing process said Novavax has recently shown purity levels hovering around 70 percent." "In a statement, Novavax Senior Vice President of Investor Relations and Corporate Affairs Silvia Taylor told POLITICO that the company’s analytical testing methods have been “validated” — but did not answer questions about whether the FDA had signed off on them. The company still plans on filing an emergency use authorization by the end of the year, Taylor said." "Novavax — which has never produced a vaccine before — declined to answer specific questions about its product’s purity levels and whether it had been successful in addressing its longstanding manufacturing issues." "U.S. officials working with the company are not as confident, according to three people with knowledge of the matter. Novavax’s manufacturing problems are seen as far more difficult to fix than the sanitary and design concerns that halted production of J&J’s vaccine at the Emergent plant earlier this year, those people said." "four people with knowledge of the matter say U.S. officials now no longer expect the company to win FDA sign-off on the vaccine until next year at the earliest." https://www.politico.com/news/2021/10/19/novavax-vaccine-rush-process-global-campaign-516298

Time is running out, and Novavax is still talking about submitting an application by the end of the year. And there are apparently doubts about whether the FDA will sign off on its manufacturing processes. Not looking likely for the end of the year. I was too optimistic for this question, which has turned into a Brier bomb for me.
Paging Novavax followers. What do y'all think about the Phase 3 data and the EUA goal?

Novavax Phase 3 results are finally out, and good! They came out yesterday. No word on exactly when an EUA application will be submitted, but I am optimistic that it will be soon. I'm fairly certain the FDA will approve their submission, so imo, it's mainly about whether they submit an EUA application in time for authorization by the end of the year. https://twitter.com/Novavax/status/1447571753769832455 And I have zero probabilities on higher numbers because I don't think any other vaccine is in the running at this point. Medicago would be the only possibility, but we haven't heard any statement from them about going for FDA authorization or approval at all.
Time is running out for an EUA application to be submitted in time to be approved. I haven't given up on Novavax yet, but I have given up on Medicago.

The Sanofi mRNA vaccine is out of the picture. (Not that it was really that much in the running, but it is now formally out.) It also looks like the Sanofi/GSK protein vaccine is very likely out for the forecast period, as companies seem to be waiting for completion of Phase 3 trials to apply for an EUA at this point. "[Sanofi] plans to push forward on production of a recombinant protein Covid vaccine, work it is doing in collaboration with GSK. ... Sanofi hopes to have readouts by the end of this year on the Phase 3 trial of its recombinant vaccine as a primary Covid vaccine, as well as results of ongoing trials testing the Sanofi jab as a booster for other vaccines." https://www.statnews.com/2021/09/28/with-positive-data-on-mrna-covid-vaccine-sanofi-sets-its-sights-on-other-pathogens/

With no additional FDA filings in the last month and the "fastest approval in FDA history" having taken four months to review, it seems increasingly unlikely that additional vaccines with be approved in 2021. So, adjusting my forecast to reflect most likely outcome is no additional vaccine approvals this year, with smaller chance that Astra-Zeneca or Novavax decide to file.
Shuffling down with time,
Still confident that Novavax will submit an EUA next month, which I expect to get approved in November as the winter wave hits.
Local news in Chattanooga TN claims Novovax is "getting ready" to seek "full approval" .... in the "coming months." https://www.wdef.com/novavax-vaccine-getting-ready-to-apply-for-full-approval/

All companies realistically need to file at least by the end of November for there to be a chance at an EUA. The time window is narrowing. 3 currently authorized. Maybe, in order of what I think is the likelihood of FDA authorization/approval happening in 2021: * Novavax (EUA application to be filed in 4th quarter) * Sanofi GSK protein ("The companies are projecting a possible regulatory approval in the fourth quarter of 2021." Trials funded by BARDA/DoD, so FDA authorization/approval will likely be sought.) * Medicago (got FDA Fast Track designation in Feb; positive Phase 2 results; no news for a while) * Sanofi mRNA * AZ (will likely apply for full approval directly; almost certainly wouldn't get approval by the end of 2021; reportedly considering getting out of Covid vaccine business) I think Novavax and Sanofi/GSK are most likely but not shoe-ins. I think seeing at least one more authorization by the end of the year is likely.

Updating forecast. FDA has either approved (EUA or full) three vaccines already: Pfizer, Moderna, and J&J. Based on approval in the EU already, two most likely candidates to file with the FDA are AstraZeneca in Q3 [1] and Novavax in Q4 [2]. Other candidates seem unlikely to seek US approval. The full approval of the Pfizer vaccine took four months, the "fastest vaccine approval in FDA history' [3]. So, AstraZeneca seems possible, with Novavax increasingly unlikely to get approval by year end.

Pending clarification, small bump in 2 or fewer juuuuuust in case a full approval wouldn't count. I'm pretty sure it would still count as an approved vaccine. Feels weird to come up from 0% and become uncertain again... at 1%. It would be fun to see a game where assigning a 0% or 100% probability to a bin would disqualify you from continuing to update the forecast. So in other words if you are 0% sure something will not happen but change your mind a teeny-weeny bit to 1%, this would not be possible.

My thinking is that because of the needed boosters, the FDA will approve vaccines that give them confidence that (a) one dose is enough or (b) that boosters are safe and the company has enough in supply. Imagine FDA approving a vaccine where there's just going to be growing ineffectiveness to Delta and its sublineages. Imagine FDA approving a vaccine where its boosters are not proven to be safe. Or imagine FDA approving new vaccines with boosters but there is so much demand that it overwhelms the company or overwhelms any budget the government has in purchasing them. Again, I am rather ignorant on this topic so I cannot say for sure.

Here are my old expectations, but updated a bit. I'd be absolutely flabbergasted if the FDA rescended approval for the shots that have already proven effective at fighting this. Novavax seems ready to file their paperwork and MAY receive emergency authorization or even full approval by year end because their vaccine is being proven against the current variants instead of old hat - they also only need fridge temps and have more mild side effects. AZ seems determined to not file any paperwork until later this year and there's no scientific reason for the FDA to rush that through the process so I'm downgrading their likelihood of authorization.

There are currently 3 approved for emergency use (Pfizer, Moderna, J&J). No reason to assume that these 3 won't continue to be approved (either for emergency use or as full approval). Novavax will likely submit for emergency use in Q3, and given its trial results should be likely to be approved in Q4. AstraZeneca doesn't seem on track to be approved in 2021 (likely to submit for full approval (not emergency) towards the end of the year, the full approval will probably take more time). No other promising candidates.

It seems that the AZ application for full approval isn't even in yet, while they aren't even trying for an EUA. I'm reducing the chances they get approval/authorization before the end of the year. NovaVax, on the other hand, looks more promising to get an EAU in Nov/Dec (especially if there is another flair up in the colder months). I still don't see any others that look on pace.
Pfizer, Moderna, JnJ plus probably Novavax and Astrazeneca.

Ocugen is likely out for 2021 approval. @SE_Meyer, thought you'd be interested: "OCGN announced that it will submit a biologics license application (“BLA”) for its COVID-19 vaccine candidate, Covaxin, in the United States following the FDA's recommendation. If 4 is more likely, than so is the tendency for 5 to be greater than 3. Therefore I shifted percentage points from 3 bin to 5 bin and some to the 6 bin to widen the net for a possible but unlikely approval spree. I understand the justification for 3 remaining the status quo because America doesn't need them as much anymore, but it is quite possible that officials want to push closer to herd immunity and give the widely acceptable and considered options a shot, pun unintended.

With the downfall trend in vaccination rates, there may be some kind of campaign, intentional or not, to provide at least one more option for America but it has been a while so the slowness in approval and the decreased urgency for it in terms of COVID rates and vaccine availability makes me doubt the 6 or more bin.

Expecting the Novavax vaccine to complete trials in June or later according to the WP [https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2021/05/10/novavax-coronavirus-vaccine/]. If Pfizer and Moderna are appropriate indicators, the Novavax vaccine could be approved within a month of submission, but it's likely that Pfizer and Moderna (and us) were lucky to see miraculous results just weeks before the winter season when cases were expected to overwhelm hospitals further. New daily cases were eight times higher than they are now, and the rate of daily first dose vaccinations is dropping pretty fast. As others mentioned, it seems it would be more difficult for the FDA to justify further vaccine EUAs.

Baseline assumption is that there is not time for another new vaccine to get approval in this window, other than AstraZeneca and Novavax. This leaves the highest reasonable outcome at five (including the three already approved). The question then turns to whether the new two get authorization and if the existing three remain under an EUA. On that front, Pfizer is already pursuing full FDA approval and the J&J pause highlights the risk of revocation. AstraZeneca is contemplating skipping EUA.
